  ('About how many people may have lived in Alexandria during the early Roman period?', 'Roughly 500,000.', '300,000–700,000', 500000, 'people', 'Cities & Archaeology', 'Alexandria was one of the Mediterranean''s largest centers of trade, scholarship and Jewish life.', 'Acts 18:24', 'Acts 27:6', 'Historical population estimate', 'https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2024/dec/25/birth-jesus-plague-roman-empire-christianity'),
  ('About how many people may have lived in Antioch of Syria in the Roman period?', 'Roughly 200,000–250,000.', '150,000–300,000', 225000, 'people', 'Cities & Archaeology', 'Antioch was one of the Roman East''s largest cities and became a major early-Christian center.', 'Acts 11:19–26', 'Acts 13:1–3', 'Historical population estimate', 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roman_Syria'),
  ('About how many people probably lived in Nazareth when Jesus grew up there?', 'Probably only a few hundred; use about 400.', '200–500', 400, 'people', 'Cities & Archaeology', 'Archaeology indicates Nazareth was a small Jewish village, not a major city. Modern scholarly estimates have been revised downward.', 'Matthew 2:23', 'Luke 4:16–30', 'Archaeological estimate', 'https://www.biblicalarchaeology.org/daily/biblical-sites-places/exploring-jesuss-hometown/'),
  ('About how many people may have lived in Capernaum during Jesus''s ministry?', 'Roughly 1,200–1,700.', '1,000–2,000', 1450, 'people', 'Cities & Archaeology', 'Capernaum was a fishing village and ministry base for Jesus, but it lacked the monumental structures of a large city.', 'Matthew 4:13', 'Mark 2:1–4', 'Archaeological estimate', 'https://davidbcapes.com/articles/brief-articles/first-century-capernaum/'),
  ('Using a modern archaeological demographic model, about how many people may Roman Ephesus have held?', 'About 70,000.', '50,000–100,000', 71587, 'people', 'Cities & Archaeology', 'Older popular estimates reached 200,000 or more, but newer models often produce substantially lower figures.', 'Acts 19:23–41', 'Revelation 2:1–7', 'Archaeological estimate', 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ephesus'),
  ('About how many urban residents may Roman Corinth have had in Paul''s day?', 'Roughly 30,000–50,000 urban residents.', '30,000–60,000', 40000, 'urban residents', 'Cities & Archaeology', 'The wider territory likely held additional rural residents. Population estimates for Roman Corinth differ substantially.', 'Acts 18:1–11', '1 Corinthians 1:2', 'Historical population estimate', 'https://kmooreperspective.blogspot.com/2015/12/the-ancient-city-of-corinth.html'),
  ('About how many people may have lived in Bethlehem when Jesus was born?', 'A common estimate is about 300.', '200–1,000', 300, 'people', 'Cities & Archaeology', 'Bethlehem was probably a small Judean village, which fits its description as an unexpectedly humble birthplace.', 'Matthew 2:1–6', 'Luke 2:4–7', 'Archaeological estimate', 'https://biblearchaeologyreport.com/2021/12/10/o-little-town-of-bethlehem-2/');